        <h1 id="the-parse-database">Android Calculator</h1>
<p>Before you start the lab please update your Android Studio to version 1.5.2. If that is not available
for you then update to 2.3.2 stable version. If you did your pre-lab after 10 am today you do not do this step
as the page was updated to install the 1.5.2 version. When open
the Android Studio click on the <strong>gear wheel</strong> on the right bottom of the screen and click
on the <strong>check for updates</strong> option. Next click on <strong>Update and restart</strong> button
to update to 1.5.2 or 2.3.2 version, and make sure everything goes fine. Once the update is complete continue with the lab. Some parts could be little
different but nothing major should be different than the 1.5.1 version</p></br>

<h2 id="parse">Unit 1: Introduction to Android</h2>
<ul>
  <li>What is Android?
    <ul>
      <li>Android as many may know is an operating system offered by Google for mobile 
          devices. It uses java under the hood with many API offered by developers. An 
          application programming interface or API 
          is a library provided by other developers to facilitate certain generic 
          functionalities for Android developers to use. You could read more about it 
          <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Application_programming_interface" 
          target="_blank">here</a>. Android applications can be developed for both phones 
          tablets that are running on Android OS. The latest version of Android at the 
          momment is called Android Nougat. IF intrested, more information can be accessed 
          <a href="https://plus.google.com/communities/100109051988417688444" target="_blank">here</a>. 
          In the following lab some of the basic concepts will be covered to help get 
          aspiring Android developers to start exploring possibilties. The following lab is not a 
	  comprehensive tutorial but instead is a great start to an enjoyable adventure that 
          will hopefully inspire many great projects and products to come. Be bold, limitless 
          and don't be afraid of possibitlies.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Why Android?
    <ul>
      <li>In CSE110 there is 10 weeks (really more like 8) to develop an application that 
          works from the ground up and Android offers a great platfrom with a vibrant community
          and Google offers regular updates with
          new API every year that is announced during <a href="https://events.google.com/io2016/" 
          target="_blank">Google I/O event</a>.
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>In order to get the In Progress Check you will need to run the <strong>First Application</strong> application successfuly 
      on the day of the lab during your specific lab reservation time. </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="dependcies">Unit 2: Requirements</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Follow the pre-lab on how to download and install the 
      <a href="http://ieng6.ucsd.edu/~cs110x/static/labs/lab3/index1.html" target="_blank">
      Android Studio</a></li>
<li>Start a new project. 
    <ul>      <li> Once the Android Studio program is launched click on the "Start a new 
                   Android Studio project" to create the first project.<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image1.15.png" alt="image1" /></li>
              <li> Name the application "FirstApplication"<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image2.png" alt="image2" /></li>
              <li> The next page asks for the form factors and minimum SDK that a develpor 
                   would like their application to run on. The minimum SDK refers to the version 
                   of android any device running the application will be required to have in order 
                   to run properly. Select "API 15: Android 4.0.3(IceCreamSandwich) and click Next
		   <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image3.png" alt="image3" />
              </li>
              <li>Next there will be series of template "Activities" to add to the application. 
                  Selecting these activities will configure the application for specific tasks 
                  such as the "Login Activity". For now select the "Basic Activity" and select Next. 
                  Later additonal activities could be added.
		  <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image4.png" alt="image4" />
              </li>
              <li>Name the activity HelloWorld and click Finish. Android studio will now create the
                  project.
              </li>
              <li>The project will now generates all the necessary files to create the application 
                  which will load in a window similar the one below after about 1-2 minutes.
                      <ul><li>Note: if the project view (left side of the screen) looks different than 
                          the image below, click the dropdown menu in the upper left (labeled "Android") 
                          and change the view to match.
                      </li>
                      <li>Alternatively navigate to FirstApplication -&gt; app -&gt; src -&gt; main -&gt; 
                          java -&gt; com.mycompany.firstapplication -&gt; HelloWorld.java
                      </li></ul>
		      <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image5.png" alt="image5" />
              </li>
    </ul>
  </li>

<h2 id="creating">Unit 3: Creating Android Projects</h2>
  <li>Creating an Android Virtual machine.
          <ul><li>Next, right click on the canvas (where the code is) and select <strong>Run 'HelloWorld'</strong> 
                  or click the play button at the top of the screen. The program will then compile 
                  and a pop up window will display after some time prompting to select a virtual machine.
		  <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image6.png" alt="image6" />
		  </li>
              <li>Click the <strong>...</strong> to the right of the drop down box to create a virtual machine to run the
                  program in that environment.<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image7.png" alt="image7" /></li>
              <li>Select <strong>Create a virtual device</strong>. The user will be prompted to a new screen asking
                  to select a category, select <strong>Phone</strong>. A list of phone models will appear to the 
                  right of the screen select the <strong>Nexus 5</strong>. If the machine being used has 2GB or less 
                  dedicated to the Virtual Machine, then choosing <strong>Nexus 4</strong>instead is recomended.
		  <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image8.png" alt="image8" /></li>
              <li>Next select the API that the VM Phone will run. Select the x86 appropriate to the machine being used. 
                  X86_64 for 64 bit machines and x86 for 32 bit machines. Click Next and choose the latest version of 
                  android <strong>Nougat</strong>. Click <strong>Download</strong><img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image10.png" alt="image9" /></li>
              <li>Once the desired version has been downloaded then click on the <strong>next</strong> button.
		  <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image10.png" alt="image10" /></li>
              <li>In the next step a screen will be presented to finalize the emulator. Leave the defaults values 
                  selected and select <strong>finish</strong>. The virtual machine will then be created. This may 
                  take a few moments, especially if the program is running on VMware. If the emulator is running
                  really slow then using a physical android phone will be more convinient. Just hook up the
                  device to the machine and choose the device from the connected devices instead choosing an emulator
                  (There is a description few steps back on this topic).<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image11.png" alt="image11" /></li>
              <li>When the VM is created the AVD Manager will appear. This is the screen where you can manage all the various virtual
                  devices that have been created in order to test the android application. Choose the device and click <strong>Ok</strong>
		  <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image13.png" alt="image12" /></li>
              <li>At this point the system should boot up the VM and run the program that was just created.If 
                  nothing happens close Android Studio and reopen it. Try to run the program again</li> 
                  <ul><li>If one of the errors shown in the images below occurs try the following fixes
		          <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image14.png" alt="image1" /><img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image15.png" alt="image14" /></li>
                      <li><strong>Linux Users:</strong> to fix shut down the Virtual Machine and click Edit 
                          virtual machine settings -&gt; Processors. Click to enable Virtualize Intel <strong>VT-x/EPT</strong>
                          or <strong>AMD-V/RVI</strong><img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image16.png" alt="image15" /></li>
                      <li>If the KVM issue occurs as seen in the image please follow the direction on this
                          <a href="https://help.ubuntu.com/community/KVM/Installation" target="_blank">
                          link</a></li> 
                  </ul>
              <li><strong>Not for Mac users</strong>
                   <ul><li>If the error shown below occurs use this 
			   <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image17.png" alt="image16" />
			   <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/21031903/how-to
                           -fix-hax-is-not-working-and-emulator-runs-in-emulation-mode" target="_blank">stack overflow</a>
                           to fix the issue. Seek help from tutors in case having difficulty.</li>
                           <li>Sudo change the HAXM installation by setting the HAXM memory to be 1024MB. Unfortunately
			       the only way to change the HAXM memory is by installing it again.
			       <code>cd ~/Library/Android/sdk/extras/intel/Hardware_Accelerated_Execution_Manageri</br>
			       OR</br>cd ~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/android-sdk-macosx/extras/intel/Hardware_Accelerated_Execution_Manager</code>
			       </br>May need to change permission.</br><code>sudo chmod 755 "HAXM installation"</code></br>
			       <code>sudo ./"HAXM installation" -m 1024</br> ./HAXM\ installation -m 1024</code></li>
                           <li>Set Virtual Machine to match by going to tools menu -&gt; Android -&gt; AVD manager
                               and then click on the pen image on the right end of the screen. Click on the advanced
                               settings and chnage the virtual device size to be the same as HAXM memory limit.
			       <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image18.png" alt="image18" /></li>
		  </ul>
              </li>
	      <li>If using a windows machine and get the below error<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image19.png" alt="image19" />
		<ul><li>Navigate to the SDK manager and check the intel x86 emulator and click install to begin the download</li>
		    <li>Open the windows Run window by entering<strong>Windows + R</strong>. Then enter "cmd" into
			this window and click ok.<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image20.png" alt="image20" /></li>
		    <li>Now the Windows Command Prompt window should open. Navigate to the location of the SDK directory
			<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image21.png" alt="image21" /></li>
		    <li>In this directory go to extras -&gt; intel -&gt; Hardware_Accelerated_Execution_Manager and run the
			file named "intelhaxm-android.exe".<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image22.png" alt="image22" /></li> 
		    <li>Once the execution manager window pops up, select 2.0 GB as the amount of RAM to allow intel HAXM to use.</li>
		    <li>Now restart the Android Studio and then try to start the AVD again</li>
		</ul>
	      </li>
	      <li>Device should load up your application and run the <strong>First Application</strong> application
                  <ul><li>If for some reason the "Hello World!" is not being displayed right away, click run a second time  and that will reload
			  the application.</li>
		  </ul><img src="/~cs110x/static/img/newLab3/image23.png" alt="image23" />
	      </li>
          </ul>
	<h1 id="check-point----">â€” <strong>In Progress Check</strong> â€”</h1>

